      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is decision-first AI?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Decision-first AI is an approach where you start by defining the specific business decision you want to improve, then build AI models optimized for that decision outcome - not just prediction accuracy. This prevents dataset-first traps where models are built without clear business impact."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the Decision Map framework?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Decision Map is a six-step framework for implementing decision-first AI: 1) Name the decision (who decides, how often), 2) Define the decision metric(s), 3) Map the current process, 4) Identify the minimal action the model must trigger, 5) List minimal signals (data) needed, 6) Plan the feedback loop. Complete this before touching any data."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does dataset-first AI fail?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dataset-first projects optimize for prediction metrics (RMSE, F1, AUC) but don't connect to actual business decisions. Models with better accuracy can still be useless if they don't change what someone does. This leads to failed adoption, brittle production systems, and wasted resources."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are examples of decision-first AI in production?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Real examples include: 1) Telecom DSL fault prediction reducing detection time from days to hours, saving ¬£80K/month through planned vs reactive dispatches. 2) Inventory forecasting delivering $11M in optimization by aligning forecasts with merchant reorder decisions and supply constraints, not just minimizing MAPE."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I start implementing decision-first AI?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Start with a one-hour Decision Map workshop. Invite the decision owner, one operator, one engineer, and one product owner. Build the one-page map defining: decision name, metrics, owner, frequency, action triggered, minimal signals, baseline rule, and feedback source. If the owner can't commit to a metric, pause the project."
      }
    }
  ]
